      <trans-unit id="10591" identifier="086e3f89f7af73af72bb61845de07891">
        <source>For the 11 digits entered, you need to add up 1st, 3rd, 5th and so on
digits and store the result in a variable called total 1.</source>
        <target>crwdns10591:0crwdne10591:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10592" identifier="fd34f7e35169be9442b4891f41cf23b5">
        <source>Then add up 2nd, 4th, 6th and so on digits and store the result in
variable called total 2.</source>
        <target>crwdns10592:0crwdne10592:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10593" identifier="90bb16846e6bdc2989cd6cdb015cab0e">
        <source>The last digit (check digit) is then calculated by subtracting the sum
of total 1 multiplied by 3 and total 2 from 0 mod 10.</source>
        <target>crwdns10593:0crwdne10593:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10594" identifier="e2aa61a5297836a915b474af95177cb4">
        <source>You can access a letter (or a digit) at a specified position in a string
(or number) by using the &lt;code&gt;scratch:letter () of []&lt;/code&gt; block under “Operators”.</source>
        <target>crwdns10594:0crwdne10594:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li[2]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
      <trans-unit id="10595" identifier="e584e8f911b1db14b71f83f33959d99f">
        <source>For example: &lt;code&gt;scratch:letter (4) of [18392819202910] //9&lt;/code&gt;</source>
        <target>crwdns10595:0[18392819202910]crwdne10595:0</target>
        <note>Context: XPath: /ul/li[2]/p</note>
      </trans-unit>
